      <section id="home">
        <h1>Paul Debevec<br>Software Engineer</h1>
        <p> <%= @quote.text %><br><%= @quote.author %></p>
      </section>
      <section id="about">
        <h1 style="padding-bottom: 10vh">About</h1>
        <p><%= File.read('lib/about.txt') %></p>
      </section>

      <section id="projects">
        <div style="padding-bottom: 15vh">
          <h1>Project Experience</h1>
        </div>
        <div class="section group" style="padding-bottom: 20vh">
          <a href="/projects/sweater-weather"><h2>Sweater Weather</h2></a>
          <div class="col span_2_of_2">
            <img src="../images/sweater-weather/see-you-soon.png" alt="see you soon sign" style="height 100px">
          </div>
        	<div class="col span_1_of_2">
            <p>Sweater Weather is a solo project at Turing School of Software & Design. It's an application that utilizes the Google Maps API, NREL Weather API, Unsplash API and the Zomato API. The goal of this project was to expose several endpoints after receiving a user input current location and destination. These endpoints would return JSON objects of the destination weather (hourly & daily), nearby restaurants at their destination. The unsplash API will display a background image based on their destination. Click the project name to view details.</p>
        	</div>
        </div>

        <div class="section group" style="padding-bottom: 20vh">
          <a href="/projects/solarizer"><h2>Solarizer</h2></a>
          <div class="col span_2_of_2">
            <img src="https://alumni.turing.io/sites/default/files/styles/project_screenshot/public/project_screenshots/Screen%20Shot%202020-08-19%20at%209.53.26%20AM.png?itok=atUVAjEW" alt="solarizer app photo">
          </div>
        	<div class="col span_1_of_2">
            <p>Solarizer allows for users to configure a hypothetical solar power generation system through a series of forms to predict monthly energy output and utility savings. After configuration, the user is provided data in a table and can choose to view the same datapoints as several types of charts. We hope that having access to this information in a friendly user interface will encourage wider adoption of green energy sources. Click the project name to view details.</p>
        	</div>
        </div>

        <div class="section group" style="padding-bottom: 20vh">
          <a href="/projects/garden-that"><h2>Garden That</h2></a>
          <div class="col span_2_of_2">
            <img src="https://alumni.turing.io/sites/default/files/styles/project_screenshot/public/project_screenshots/Screen%20Shot%202020-08-19%20at%2010.02.51%20AM.png?itok=P1G8Cyfz" alt="garden that landing page">
          </div>
          <div class="col span_1_of_2">
            <p>GardenThat is an application meant for any gardener. Search a selection of fruit and vegetable bearing plants. Add your favorite plants to your Garden. Automated calendar notifications tell you when to expect your first harvest. Click the project name to view details.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section group" style="padding-bottom: 20vh">
          <a href="/projects/jam-session"><h2>Jam Session</h2></a>
          <div class="col span_2_of_2">
            <img src="https://alumni.turing.io/sites/default/files/styles/project_screenshot/public/project_screenshots/Screen%20Shot%202020-08-19%20at%2010.11.50%20AM.png?itok=lnxvZwBt" alt="garden that landing page">
          </div>
          <div class="col span_1_of_2">
            <p>Jam Session is a Ruby on Rails application used to provide a central hub for categorized, timed study sessions. Users can connect their Spotify account to have music access/control while using the application. Users are provided with a new quote for inspiration with every dashboard and study session visit. Users can see their previous study sessions topics and time durations, giving the ability to monitor time spent on topics or to quickly clone a similar session. Click the project name to view details.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </section>
